onnx bundles for sd dont have naming or directory structure conducive to putting them in  the same folder.

trying to come up with an elegant solution to allow multiple sd file groups with minimal renaming/moving/selection after downloading them

ux: swap from sd no optimization to sd fp16 then swap out the unet model for one downloaded and converted off civitai optimized for pixel art





You want a solution that is elegant in three different ways at once:

it should preserve upstream downloads as much as possible
it should let multiple SD bundles coexist cleanly
it should make model swapping feel natural in the UI

That is the right instinct. Renaming and hand-curating folders is exactly the kind of friction Beast should absorb.

The cleanest answer is: do not make the downloaded folder structure the runtime structure.

Instead, treat each ONNX bundle as an imported model group artifact, then project it into a Beast-managed logical structure.

In other words:

download layout = messy external reality
beast model registry = clean internal truth

So I would avoid forcing users to manually rename or merge files into one canonical shared folder. That will get glitchy fast, especially once you have different bundles with different tokenizer, text encoder, vae, scheduler, unet, fp16/fp32 variants, and conversion quirks.

A strong architecture is this:

1. keep imports mostly intact

When the user downloads an ONNX SD bundle, Beast imports it as a group.
That group gets:
	•	a stable Beast id
	•	source path
	•	detected components
	•	component roles
	•	precision info
	•	conversion provenance
	•	compatibility tags

Example mental model:

sd_group_001 = sd no optimization
sd_group_002 = sd fp16
sd_group_003 = civitai pixel art unet

Do not require perfect upstream naming. Beast should inspect files and infer likely roles.

2. separate logical roles from file names

Internally, Beast should care about roles like:
	•	text_encoder
	•	text_encoder_2
	•	tokenizer
	•	tokenizer_2
	•	vae_decoder
	•	vae_encoder
	•	unet
	•	scheduler_config
	•	model_index
	•	config

Not about whether the upstream file was named nicely.

So the registry row says, effectively:

this file path fulfills unet for this group
this file path fulfills vae_decoder for this group

That means ugly downloaded names stop mattering.

3. define a "base group + overrides" model

This feels like your real UX target.

For example:

base:
	•	sd no optimization group

swap preset:
	•	sd fp16 group

override:
	•	unet = civitai pixel art unet group

That is much better than making users manually assemble a frankenfolder.

So the active runtime model becomes a resolved composition:

base group
	•	optional optimized variant
	•	optional component overrides

That gives you exactly the workflow you described:

swap from sd no optimization
→ sd fp16
→ replace only unet with pixel-art-optimized one

And the user experiences it as selection, not file surgery.

4. make Beast generate the resolved runtime view

At execution time, Beast can materialize a resolved view in one of two ways:

Either a temporary runtime manifest that points to the selected component files, or a generated Beast-managed runtime folder/symlink layout.

The important thing is that the user should not have to manually build this layout.

So:

import once
tag components
compose logically
run from resolved view

5. UI should show "family" and "part"

A good UX shape is:

model family
	•	SD 1.5 base
	•	SD 1.5 fp16
	•	SDXL base
	•	etc.

active components
	•	text encoder: from fp16 bundle
	•	vae: from fp16 bundle
	•	unet: from pixel art bundle
	•	tokenizer: from fp16 bundle

This makes the swap inspectable.

That matters because once users start mixing components, hidden state becomes wtf quickly.

6. preserve low-friction imports with a staging area

I would strongly consider:

imports/
keep raw downloaded bundles here, mostly untouched

registry.db
stores detected groups and roles

runtime/
generated resolved layouts or manifests

This avoids destructive moves and lets Beast re-scan or repair imports later.

7. support "component compatibility confidence"

Because not every swapped unet will actually match cleanly.

So Beast should assign something like:
	•	compatible
	•	likely compatible
	•	unknown
	•	mismatch

Based on:
	•	model family
	•	tensor shapes
	•	architecture markers
	•	expected inputs
	•	precision
	•	known metadata

Then the UI can say:

"swap unet from pixel-art bundle"
status: likely compatible

That is much better than silent breakage.

8. save this as a reusable "model preset"

Once the user makes a good combo, it should become a named Beast preset or artifact.

Example:

sd15_fp16_pixel_art_v1
	•	base group: sd15 fp16
	•	override unet: civitai pixel art unet
	•	scheduler: euler a
	•	notes: good for sprite work

That fits Beast perfectly: the composition becomes reusable and inspectable.

⸻

The simplest elegant rule is:

users import bundles, Beast resolves components

not:

users manually normalize folders until the app is happy

That is the right lazy design.

A concise internal design formulation might be:

raw in import
roles in db
resolved at runtime

Or in Beast tone:

keep download mess outside
keep clean truth in beast db
build runtime view on demand

For the exact UX you described, I would model it as:
	•	choose base model group
	•	choose optimization variant
	•	optionally override components
	•	save as runtime preset

That gives you minimal renaming, minimal moving, minimal reselection, and maximum clarity.

The only thing I would strongly avoid is a single flat shared folder with copied renamed files from many bundles. It sounds simple at first, but once people mix several SD families and variants, it will become fragile and confusing fast.

A good Beast note for this would be:

onnx imports stay raw
beast maps files to roles
runtime model = base group + overrides

That feels like the elegant solution here.








sdxl differences from sd










The difference between Stable Diffusion (often SD 1.x/2.x) and SDXL is not just "a bigger model." It is a shift in how the model understands prompts, composes images, and handles detail.

Core idea

SD = single-stage, smaller context, weaker prompt grounding
SDXL = dual-stage, larger context, stronger structure and detail

That shows up everywhere in practice.

⸻

1. Architecture and prompting

SD (1.5, 2.x)
	•	One main text encoder (CLIP-based)
	•	Shorter effective prompt understanding
	•	Tends to "average" prompts
	•	Needs tricks (weights, negative prompts, prompt engineering)

SDXL
	•	Dual text encoders (CLIP variants)
	•	Much stronger prompt comprehension
	•	Better at long, structured descriptions
	•	More literal interpretation of prompt components

In Beast terms:
SD feels like "suggestion"
SDXL feels closer to "instruction"

⸻

2. Composition and structure

SD
	•	Can drift compositionally
	•	Faces and bodies degrade at higher complexity
	•	Needs strong anchoring ("full body, centered, etc.")

SDXL
	•	Much better scene layout
	•	More consistent anatomy
	•	Handles multiple elements more reliably
	•	Better spatial reasoning

This connects directly to what you saw:

weak prompt → SD defaults to "safe prior" (town scene)
SDXL is less likely to collapse that way because it holds structure better

⸻

3. Resolution and detail

SD
	•	Native ~512px (SD1.5), ~768px (SD2)
	•	Upscaling needed for detail
	•	Fine detail often mushy or inconsistent

SDXL
	•	Native ~1024px
	•	Much sharper out of the box
	•	Better textures, lighting, material definition

This is not just size -- it is learned detail fidelity.

⸻

4. Two-stage generation (important)

SDXL pipeline often uses:
	1.	base model → composition, layout, main image
	2.	refiner model → detail, texture, polish

SD does everything in one pass.

This matters for your architecture thinking:

SD = one generator step
SDXL = naturally two-step generator (fits Beast pipelines well)

⸻

5. Style behavior

SD
	•	Strong style bias depending on checkpoint
	•	Easier to "bend" into stylized outputs (anime, pixel art, etc.)
	•	Sometimes less consistent but more flexible

SDXL
	•	More "photographic default"
	•	Cleaner, more realistic outputs
	•	Harder to force into extreme styles without specialized models

So:

SD → easier for pixel art, stylized generators
SDXL → better for clean, realistic, structured scenes

This is important for your goblin/pixel experiments.

⸻

6. Model ecosystem

SD (1.5 especially)
	•	Massive ecosystem
	•	Tons of finetunes, LoRAs, niche styles
	•	Lightweight, fast, flexible

SDXL
	•	Growing ecosystem
	•	Heavier models
	•	Fewer niche finetunes (but improving)

So for Beast:

SD = huge generator library potential
SDXL = higher baseline quality, fewer specialized tools (for now)

⸻

7. Performance / hardware

SD
	•	Faster
	•	Lower VRAM
	•	Easier to run many variants (good for Beast exploration loops)

SDXL
	•	Slower
	•	Higher VRAM
	•	Heavier pipelines (especially with refiner)

So:

SD → exploration, variant farming
SDXL → higher-quality final passes

⸻

8. Failure modes

This is where your observations connect nicely.

SD failure modes
	•	collapses to default scenes (like your town example)
	•	bad anatomy
	•	prompt drift
	•	unstable subjects ("boy", "goblin" issues)

SDXL failure modes
	•	overly literal / stiff outputs
	•	harder to stylize
	•	heavier compute cost
	•	sometimes "too clean" / less character

⸻

9. How this fits Beast2 thinking

This is the interesting part for your system design.

You are not choosing one. You are composing both.

A strong pattern:
	•	SD generators → exploration, variants, style discovery
	•	SDXL generators → refinement, structure, final outputs

That maps cleanly to:

generator A (SD) → find diamonds
generator B (SDXL) → refine diamonds

That aligns with your "diamond / ok / landfill" artifact system.  ￼

⸻

10. Quick mental model

If you want a simple way to think about it:

SD:
	•	creative
	•	messy
	•	flexible
	•	fast
	•	sometimes dumb

SDXL:
	•	structured
	•	sharp
	•	literal
	•	slower
	•	more reliable

⸻

Final thought

Your earlier observations (town default, goblin/boy issues) are very "SD-class behavior."

SDXL would likely:
	•	reduce default scene collapse
	•	handle "goblin child" better structurally
	•	but might resist stylization unless you guide it harder

So this is not just model comparison -- it is a generator design decision inside Beast.

You are effectively deciding:
	•	where exploration happens
	•	where structure is enforced
	•	where refinement occurs

And SD vs SDXL maps cleanly onto those roles.








any blockers to running a few unet steps to "preview" then resuming full steps to get "final"?








Not really a fundamental blocker, but there are a few practical catches.

In principle, yes: you can run a diffusion process for a small number of UNet denoise steps, show that as a preview, then continue from that same latent state to finish the run. That is much more like a true progressive preview than "generate a cheap fake and then start over."

The key condition is this:

you must preserve the exact latent state and scheduler state at the pause point.

If you have that, resuming is conceptually straightforward.

The main caveats are these.

First, scheduler bookkeeping.
It is not just "latent after step 8." The scheduler also defines which timestep you are on, and some schedulers have internal state or assumptions that matter. If Beast can serialize:
	•	current latent
	•	current step index
	•	scheduler/timestep sequence
	•	seed/noise config
	•	CFG state and prompt conditioning
	•	model/component versions

then resume should work fine.

Second, preview quality can be misleading.
Early-step previews are often structurally useful but aesthetically ugly. They may be good enough to answer:
	•	composition right?
	•	subject count right?
	•	silhouette right?
	•	camera angle roughly right?

but not:
	•	face quality
	•	texture
	•	hands
	•	final readability

So this is excellent for "continue or cancel?" but weaker for final judgment.

Third, changing anything after preview breaks continuity.
If after 8 steps the user changes prompt, CFG, resolution, ControlNet inputs, LoRA stack, or UNet, then it is no longer a true resume. At that point it becomes a branch from an intermediate latent, which can still be useful, but is not the same as continuing the original run.

Fourth, some optimizations make pause/resume awkward.
Depending on runtime:
	•	graph-captured execution
	•	fused pipelines
	•	provider-specific ONNX sessions
	•	aggressive memory reuse

may make "stop here, surface preview, then continue later" more annoying to implement cleanly, even though it is still possible architecturally.

Fifth, VAE decode cost.
If you preview often, the bottleneck may not be UNet alone. Repeatedly decoding latent to image for UI preview can add enough overhead to hurt throughput. So the elegant version is usually:
	•	sparse preview checkpoints
	•	maybe lower-frequency decode
	•	maybe lower-res or tiled preview decode

For Beast, this feels very aligned with your architecture.

A good model is:

run job
→ checkpoint latent at step N
→ optional preview artifact
→ continue to final
→ final artifact

That means the preview is itself a real artifact in lineage, not just disposable UI fluff. That fits your artifact system nicely.  ￼

The strongest use cases are:
	•	early cancel if composition is bad
	•	gallery/live lightbox preview
	•	branch from step N into alternate continuations
	•	compare schedulers or CFG from same intermediate state

That last one is especially interesting. If you preserve the step-8 latent, you can fork:
	•	final A: continue normal
	•	final B: continue with different CFG
	•	final C: continue with different sampler path if compatible

So the short answer is:

No hard blocker.
The real requirement is treating diffusion as a resumable state machine, not a black-box one-shot call.

If you want a Beast phrasing:

preview = partial denoise artifact
final = continued denoise from same latent state

or even:

gen can pause at step n
show preview
resume to final if lgtm

That seems like a very good feature direction.









steps for sd decode










If you mean how SD turns a latent into a visible image, the decode side is very short compared to denoising.

SD image path

Roughly:
	1.	start with noise latent
	2.	run many UNet denoise steps
	3.	get a final latent
	4.	run VAE decode once
	5.	output RGB image

So the important distinction is:
	•	UNet steps = many iterative diffusion steps
	•	decode = usually one VAE forward pass

There usually are not "decode steps" in the same sense.

Typical counts

For normal SD generation:
	•	UNet denoise steps: often 20–50
	•	VAE decode steps: effectively 1 pass

What VAE decode does

The final latent might be something like:
	•	4 x 64 x 64 for a 512x512 SD image

The VAE decoder expands that into:
	•	3 x 512 x 512 RGB image

So decode is more like:
	•	latent tensor in
	•	image tensor out

not:
	•	20-step iterative refinement

Why people sometimes talk like decode has "steps"

Because there are a few related things that can be confused with it:
	•	diffusion denoise steps
	•	tiled VAE decode for memory saving
	•	preview decode at intermediate denoise steps
	•	multi-stage pipelines like SDXL base + refiner

But plain SD decode itself is still usually just one decoder pass.

Beast-relevant framing

A clean mental model is:

noise -> unet steps -> final latent -> vae decode -> image

So if you are thinking about previewing:
	•	preview after step 4, 8, 12, etc. means
decode the current intermediate latent
	•	final means
decode the last latent

Same decode operation, different latent.

If you want, I can also break down exactly what happens inside VAE decode in SD, including the 8x latent upscale relation and why it is much cheaper than UNet.











