What UNet actually does each step

At a high level, each diffusion step is:

latent_t → UNet → predicted noise → scheduler → latent_(t-1)

More concretely:
	1.	You have a noisy latent at timestep t
	2.	UNet takes:
	•	latent
	•	timestep (t)
	•	text conditioning (embeddings)
	3.	UNet predicts:
	•	the noise (or variant like v-pred depending on model)
	4.	Scheduler uses that prediction to compute:
	•	a slightly cleaner latent
	5.	Repeat for next timestep

So UNet is not "building the image directly."
It is removing noise in a guided way.

⸻

The key mental model

Each step is:

"Given this noisy latent, what part is noise vs signal?"

Over time:
	•	early steps: global structure emerges
	•	mid steps: objects + layout stabilize
	•	late steps: fine detail, texture, edges

⸻

What changes across steps

Early steps (high noise)
	•	composition forms
	•	silhouettes appear
	•	big shapes
	•	very unstable detail

Middle steps
	•	subject identity locks in
	•	pose stabilizes
	•	scene structure becomes clear

Late steps
	•	textures
	•	facial features
	•	sharp edges
	•	small corrections

⸻

Why your preview idea works

If you preview at step ~5–10:

you already see:
	•	composition
	•	subject count
	•	framing

That is often enough to decide:
	•	continue
	•	cancel
	•	branch

⸻

Designing latent checkpoints in Beast

This is where it gets interesting.

You can treat intermediate latents as first-class artifacts.

Core idea

At step N:

latent_N = artifact

Then you can:
	•	decode → preview
	•	continue → final
	•	branch → alternate outcomes

⸻

Branching from a latent

This is the powerful part.

From the same latent_8, you can:

Path A (baseline)
	•	continue with same settings → final A

Path B (variation)
	•	change CFG → final B

Path C (style shift)
	•	add LoRA → final C

Path D (model swap, risky)
	•	swap UNet → final D

So:

latent_8 → multiple futures

That fits your "explore space" philosophy extremely well.

⸻

What must be stored to resume correctly

A latent alone is not enough.

You need a resume bundle:
	•	latent tensor
	•	current step index
	•	scheduler type
	•	timestep schedule
	•	seed / initial noise reference
	•	CFG value
	•	prompt embeddings (or prompt + encoder)
	•	model components (UNet, VAE, etc.)

If any of these change, behavior changes.

⸻

Safe vs unsafe branching

Important distinction:

Safe changes (usually stable)
	•	CFG adjustment
	•	sampler minor variation (same family)
	•	adding light LoRA
	•	minor prompt edits

Risky changes
	•	switching UNet
	•	switching model family (SD → SDXL)
	•	large prompt shifts
	•	resolution change

These can produce:
	•	artifacts
	•	identity collapse
	•	weird textures

But sometimes that is useful exploration.

⸻

Scheduler constraint

You can only resume if:
	•	you are continuing along the same timestep sequence

If you change:
	•	number of steps
	•	scheduler type

then you are not really "resuming" anymore.

You are doing a new trajectory starting from a mid-state.

Still useful, but different.

⸻

Performance implications

This is where Beast wins.

Instead of:

run 20 steps × 10 variants

You can:

run 8 steps once
branch into 10 variants from latent_8
finish 12 steps each

So:
	•	early expensive structure shared
	•	later detail diverges

That can save real compute.

⸻

UI / UX shape (this matters a lot)

A clean version could be:
	•	run generator
	•	show live previews at step intervals
	•	user clicks preview
	•	options:
	•	continue
	•	branch
	•	modify + branch

In lightbox:

show:
	•	step index
	•	preview image
	•	branch options

This turns diffusion into something interactive instead of batch-only.

⸻

Artifact graph mapping

This maps perfectly to your artifact system:
