more on cfg in sd












CFG in Stable Diffusion is one of those controls that feels simple but actually shapes the entire trajectory of the image.

What CFG actually is

CFG = Classifier-Free Guidance scale

At each denoise step, the model runs two predictions:
	•	unconditional (no prompt)
	•	conditional (with your prompt)

Then it combines them:

guided = uncond + cfg * (cond - uncond)

So CFG is literally:

"how hard should we push away from ‘no prompt’ toward ‘your prompt’?"

⸻

Intuition
	•	CFG = 0
→ ignore prompt completely
→ pure model prior (your "city/town default" case)
	•	CFG = 1
→ roughly just follow the model’s natural conditional output
	•	CFG > 1
→ amplify prompt influence

⸻

What increasing CFG does

As you raise CFG:

Pros
	•	stronger prompt adherence
	•	clearer subject identity
	•	less drift into default scenes
	•	better alignment with keywords

Cons
	•	oversaturation / harsh contrast
	•	"burned" details
	•	weird artifacts
	•	less natural images
	•	reduced diversity

So:

low CFG → creative / loose / prior-driven
high CFG → strict / forced / brittle

⸻

Typical ranges

For SD 1.5:
	•	3–5 → soft, creative, loose
	•	6–8 → balanced (most common)
	•	9–12 → strong enforcement
	•	13+ → often unstable / overcooked

For SDXL:
	•	usually lower CFG works better (around 4–7)

⸻

Why CFG matters for your issues

1. "town default" behavior

That is essentially:

CFG too low → model prior dominates

So raising CFG:
	•	pulls away from default scene
	•	forces subject into existence

⸻

2. "goblin boy → landfill"

Likely causes:
	•	weak or conflicting tokens
	•	model unsure how to render them

CFG interaction:
	•	too low → ignores subject → fallback scene
	•	moderate → starts forming subject
	•	too high → overfits bad interpretation → artifacts

So the sweet spot matters more for weak tokens.

⸻

CFG across steps (important insight)

CFG is applied every step, but its effect is not uniform.
	•	Early steps: affects composition strongly
	•	Mid steps: locks identity
	•	Late steps: affects texture and sharpness

This leads to a powerful idea:

CFG scheduling

Instead of constant CFG:
	•	lower CFG early (let composition form naturally)
	•	higher CFG later (enforce details)

Example:
	•	steps 0–8: CFG 5
	•	steps 8–20: CFG 8

This often gives:
	•	better composition
	•	fewer artifacts
	•	stronger final adherence

⸻

CFG and your "latent branching" idea

This is where it gets really interesting.

From the same latent at step N:

you can branch:
	•	CFG 5 → softer, more natural
